Introduction and Conversions

For this problem, we’ve been tasked with trying to solve for Hubble’s constant– whether it be constant or changing –and the parameters it depends on. We will use the data “Hubble.csv” to do so, which contains redshift and distance information for approximately 1700 galaxies and supernova. We will also make use of the Metropolis-Hastings Algorithm and Bayes’ Law.

We will be using Python for this problem, so we begin by importing the necessary libraries: pandas to create data frames, numpy for math such as random and infinity, emcee for MCMC modeling, matplotlib for graphing, corner for graphing multiple histograms, and the calc_distance model from models.py.

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import emcee
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from matplotlib.lines import Line2D
import corner
from models import calc_distance

We also loaded in the data and named it df for simplicity’s sake. Taking a quick look at it reveals the existence of six columns. The first two, CID and IDSURVEY, are mostly insignificant in our case because they refer to object IDs. However, the last four are very important. We have z (which contains redshift data), z_ERR (which contains the redshift uncertainty), MU (which contains distances as distance moduli: μ), and MU_ERR (which contains the μ uncertainty). We will need the z for calculating velocities (in kilometers per second) and MU for calculating distances (in megaparsecs). These will both be used to estimate Hubble’s constant. We will also need both error values for implementing our log Likelihoods.

df = pd.read_csv("data/Hubble.csv")
df.head()
CID IDSURVEY z z_ERR MU MU_ERR
0 2011fe 51 0.00122 0.00084 28.9987 1.516450
1 2011fe 56 0.00122 0.00084 29.0559 1.517470
2 2012cg 51 0.00256 0.00084 30.7233 0.782372
3 2012cg 56 0.00256 0.00084 30.7449 0.799068
4 1994DRichmond 50 0.00299 0.00084 30.7757 0.881212

Before we began, we also set a random seed for replicable outputs using random.seed().

np.random.seed(0)

The first step in our conversions is solving for velocities in km/s. We can refer to the formula \(v = cz\), where v represents the velocity in km/s, c represents the speed of light in km/s, and z represents the redshift. In our code, we set the speed of light as a constant and multiplied it by our z column in the data to create a new column called velocity_km_per_s.

speed_of_light = 299792.458 #km/s
df['velocity_km_per_s'] = df.z * speed_of_light

Next is the distance conversion. We referred to the formula below, where \(μ\) represents the distance moduli (the apparent magnitude minus the absolute magnitude, or \(m-M\)) and \(d_{pc}\) represents the distance in parsecs. We will need to convert this to megaparsecs after the initial parsec conversion.

\[ μ=5log_{10}(d_{pc})-5 \]

In order to use this formula to solve for the distances in parsecs, we needed to rearrange it into something more manageable.

\[ d_{pc}=10^{(\frac{μ+5}{5})} \]

Then we can implement this into code by substituting our MU column for the \(μ\) value in the formula. The result is a new column in our data called d_pc.

df['d_pc'] = 10**((df.MU+5)/5)

Using the conversion factor for parsecs to megaparsecs (\(10^{-6}\)) and the formula \(d_{Mpc}=d_{pc}\times 10^{-6}\) (where \(d_{Mpc}\) represents the distance in megaparsecs and \(d_{pc}\) represents it in parsecs), we can convert our distances to megaparsecs. This is saved under a new column in our data labeled d_Mpc.

df['d_Mpc'] = df.d_pc * 1E-6

Part A: “Close” Objects

Now that everything has been converted into the correct units, we can proceed with the actual analysis and calculations. For Part A, we will only be looking at objects within 100 Mpc of Earth. At these distances, the changing acceleration of the universe is negligible, the relationship between redshift velocity and distance will be linear, and Hubble’s constant will be unchanging.

First, we filtered for objects within 100 Mpc of Earth using the column d_Mpc.

fil_df = df[df["d_Mpc"] <= 100]

Then, we constructed a function to model this linear relationship. The formula for Hubble’s (unchanging) constant is written below, where \(c\) represents the speed of light (in km/s in our case), \(z\) represents the redshift, \(d\) represents the distance (in Mpc in our case), and \(H_0\) represents Hubble’s constant in km/s/Mpc.

\[ cz=H_0d \]

Our function, called hubble(), will take in the speed of light (km/s), the distance (Mpc), and \(H_0\) (km/s/Mpc) and return the calculated redshift.

def hubble(c, d, h0):
    return (h0*d)/c # will return z

Next, we will set up our log Prior, Likelihood, and Posterior for Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) sampling.

Our first function is that of the log Prior. It takes in the term param, which will be the \(H_0\), and contains a single condition: if h0 is less than 0, the function returns -Inf. In other words, h0’s value is impossible and has zero probability under the Prior. Otherwise, the function returns 0 (1 in log-space), which corresponds to a uniform Prior over the acceptable region.

def ln_prior(param):
    h0 = param
    if h0 < 0:
        return -np.inf
    return 0

Second is the log Likelihood, which also takes in value param. Using the function hubble(), which we created earlier, we can create our model (remember, hubble()’s output is redshift data). Then we calculate the difference between the observed redshift and the predicted redshift from the model and store them in residuals. This will help us understand how far off our predictions are from the actual data.

The last piece of the function involves our log Likelihood formula. We break it down into two terms (term1 and term2), but the complete formula is shown below in its entirety.

  • \(y_i\) = observed data
  • \(\hat{y_i}\) = model prediction for each \(y_i\)
  • \(σ\) = the standard deviation of the error (uncertainty)
  • \(n\) = number of observations

\[ LogL(θ) = -\frac{1}{2σ^2}\sum_{i=1}^n(y_i-\hat{y_i})^2-\frac{n}{2}log(2πσ^2) \]

In our function, term1 represents the first half of the formula. It penalizes bad fits, because the bigger the error, the more negative it grows.

\[ -\frac{1}{2σ^2}\sum_{i=1}^n(y_i-\hat{y_i})^2 \]

Term2 represents the second half of the formula. It is the normalizing constant from the normal distribution, and ensures that the full probability integrates to 1.

\[ -\frac{n}{2}log(2πσ^2) \]

All of this is implemented into the log Likelihood function below, which returns the sum of term1 and term2.

def ln_likelihood(param):
    model = hubble(speed_of_light, fil_df.d_Mpc, param)
    residual = fil_df.z - model
    term1 = - 0.5 * np.log(2 * np.pi * fil_df.z_ERR ** 2)
    term2 = - 0.5 * residual ** 2 / fil_df.z_ERR**2
    return sum(term1 + term2)

The final log function that we must define is the log Posterior, or probability distribution (which also takes in the single param value for h0). First, it calls our ln_prior function, which returns 0 if h0 is valid and -Inf if it’s not. If it does return -Inf, the ln_pdf also returns -Inf, which means that because the parameter set is invalid, it will have zero probability in the Posterior.

Next, the function computes the Likelihood based on our model’s predictions versus the actual data (using our ln_likelihood function) and returns the sum of the Prior and Likelihood calculations. This is the log Posterior, which tells us how probable our parameter value is, given the data and our other prior assumptions.

def ln_pdf(param):
    p = ln_prior(param)
    if p == -np.inf:
        return -np.inf
    return p + ln_likelihood(param)

Finally, it’s time to create our MCMC chains. We set our single h0 parameter to 65 km/s/Mpc, set the number of walkers to 20, and initialized our sampler using the EnsembleSampler() function from emcee (which takes in our number of walkers, our number of dimensions, and our log Posterior). Our starts are calculated using random.normal(), which generates a list of values centered around our parameter value and with a spread of 2 km/s/Mpc. Then, we run our sampler using the function run_mcmc(), which takes in starts and the number of iterations (as well as an optional progress bar). We ran our sampler for 1000 iterations to get an adequate amount of iterations.

param = [65]
num_walkers = 20
sampler = emcee.EnsembleSampler(num_walkers, 1, ln_pdf)
starts = np.random.normal(
            loc = param,
            scale = 2,
            size = (num_walkers,1))
out = sampler.run_mcmc(starts, 1000, progress=True)

To plot the resulting trace plot for our h0 parameter, we can use matplotlib and get_chain() from emcee (which selects all walkers from all chains for the first– and only –parameter). Our trace plot appears to have an obvious burn-in, where all walkers eventually converge around one value, which is shown on the graph with a red line (we gave a generous margin by selecting a burn-in of 100 iterations).

Code 
plt.plot(sampler.get_chain()[:,:,0], 'k', alpha=0.4)
plt.axvline(x=100, ymin=0, ymax=1, color='red', label='burn-in point')
plt.legend()
plt.xlabel("Iterations")
plt.ylabel("$H_0$ (km/s/Mpc)")
plt.title("$H_0$ Trace Plot")
plt.show()

We can now cut out our burn-in and flatten all walkers into a singular chain (essentially attaching one end of each walker chain to the next and effectively stacking them). We set our burn-in to 100 (as expressed previously) and use get_chain() again, this time specifying discard=burn_in and flat=True.

burn_in = 100
burned_in = sampler.get_chain(discard=burn_in, flat=True)

Next, we can create a histogram of the \(H_0\) parameter’s distribution using plt.hist(). This creates a normal looking distribution, which is important because it has an obvious peak and it drops off on both sides. This shows that the walker explored the parameter space sufficiently.

Code 
plt.hist(burned_in)
plt.xlabel("$H_0$ (km/s/Mpc)")
plt.ylabel("Count")
plt.title("Distribution of $H_0$")
plt.show()

To extract the approximate value of \(H_0\) and its uncertainty based on our post-burned-in data, we took the median and standard deviation of burned_in and printed those results out using f-strings.

Code 
print(f"H0 Median: {np.median(burned_in)} km/s/Mpc")
print(f"H0 Standard Deviation: {np.std(burned_in)} km/s/Mpc")
H0 Median: 72.78648755891429 km/s/Mpc

The final part of Part A is randomly selecting 100 sampled (post-burn-in) Hubble constants and plotting their model results back against the nearby points on a Hubble diagram.

The result is a reasonable looking fit for our objects that are 100 Mpc away or closer.

Code 
for i in range(100):
    index = np.random.random_integers(0,4000)
    model = hubble(speed_of_light, fil_df.d_Mpc, burned_in[index])

Part B: All Objects

In Part A, we looked at the Hubble constant within 100 Mpc, where it remained constant. This, however, is not an accurate view, since the constant changes with distance. If we plot our \(H_0\) fit for the “close” objects on a plot with all the data (by using the same plotting structure as Part A and replacing all fil_df references with df), we can see that, while it nicely captures linear data at small distances, objects begin to deviate from this linear trend as the distance increases. This is because the rate of the expansion of the universe has changed in the (very long) time it took for the light from these objects to reach us! It means that we have to assume the Hubble constant to be a value that has changed over the lifetime of the universe. In other words (from our perspective), the Hubble constant for objects that are closer differs from those that are farther away. The Hubble constant is no longer a constant; instead, it’s a function of \(z\), or redshift.

Code 
for i in range(100):
    index = np.random.random_integers(0,4000)
    model = hubble(speed_of_light, df.d_Mpc, burned_in[index])
    plt.plot(df.d_Mpc, model, color = 'C1', alpha = 0.1)
plt.plot(df.d_Mpc, df.z, '.')
plt.xlabel("Distance (Mpc)")
plt.ylabel("Redshift")
plt.title("Hubble Diagram ($H_0$ Fit Against All Data)")
plt.show()

So, how do we implement this? The key is to integrate over all the Hubble constant’s “past” values that light has traveled through, using the formula below. Once again, \(z\) represents redshift, \(c\) represents the speed of light (km/s), and \(d\) represents the distance (Mpc).

\[ d=(1+z)c\int_{0}^{z}\frac{dz^\prime}{H(z^\prime)} \]

This allows us to compute the Hubble constant as a function of redshift, or \(H(z)\), using the formula below with the following variables:

  • \(H_0\), which represents the value of the Hubble constant currently. It should be a positive value. (Units = km/s/Mpc)
  • \(\Omega_M\), which represents the overall matter density in the universe (both dark and light matter). It should be a value between 0 and 1. (Unitless)
  • \(\Omega_K\), which represents the overall curvature of the universe. The closer to 0 this value is, the flatter the universe, and higher values (negative or positive) indicate curvature. It should be a value between -1 and 1.(Unitless)
  • \(\Omega_\Lambda\), which reprsents the cosmological constant. It should be a value between 0 and 1. This generally represents the amount of dark energy in our universe. (Unitless)

\[ H(z)=H_0\sqrt{\Omega_M(1 + z)^3 + \Omega_K(1+z)^2 + \Omega_\Lambda} \]

Also, it should be noted that \(\Omega_M\), \(\Omega_K\), and \(\Omega_\Lambda\) are fractional proportions, meaning they should all add up to 1.

\[ \Omega_M + \Omega_K + \Omega_\Lambda = 1 \]

Clearly, we need a new model! To do this, we need to handle the integration specified above. Though we could use a numerical integration solver, such as quad, we have been provided with a pre-built model called calc_distances() (which we imported from models at the very beginning of the problem). This takes in our four parameters (\(H_0\), \(\Omega_M\), \(\Omega_K\), and \(\Omega_\Lambda\)) and integrates for us, outputting a list of distances in Mpcs.

In order to create our MCMC sampler once again (this time for four parameters), we have to recreate our log Prior, Likelihood, and Posterior once again. Though they have a similar structure to what we had before, some of the values are different.

Starting with the Prior, we have to set conditions for each of our parameters. Remember, \(H_0\) must be positive, \(\Omega_M\) must be a value between 0 and 1, \(\Omega_K\) must be a value between -1 and 1, and \(\Omega_\Lambda\) must be a value between 0 and 1. All of our \(\Omega\) terms should also add up to (approximately, with a bit of leeway) 1. The log Prior below reflects these conditions and functions in the same way as the Prior from Part A.

def ln_prior_b(params):
    h0, om_m, om_k, om_1 = params
    if h0 < 0 or om_m < 0 or om_m > 1 or om_k < -1 or om_k > 1 \
        or om_1 < 0 or om_1 > 1 or om_m+om_k+om_1 > 1.1 or om_m+om_k+om_1 < 0.9:
        return -np.inf
    return 0

Next, we construct our log Likelihood. The structure is once again very similar to Part A with some minor tweaks, the most important of which involves our model. Here, we need to swap the independent and dependent variables. That means that redshift (\(z\)) is now the independent variable and distance (\(d\)) is the dependent. However, we don’t have the error (uncertainty) term! Thankfully, we know the uncertainty in the distance modulus (MU_ERR) and can compute these using the formula below, where \(σ_d\) is the distance uncertainty in parsecs, \(μ\) is the distance modulus, and \(σ_μ\) is the distance modulus’ uncertainty term.

\[ σ_d=\frac{ln10}{5}\times 10^{\frac{1+μ}{5}} \times σ_μ \]

The result we can save as a new column in our data called d_ERR_pc. Then, using the conversion factor for parsecs to megaparsecs (\(10^{-6}\)) and the formula \(d_{Mpc}=d_{pc}\times 10^{-6}\) (where \(d_{Mpc}\) represents the distance in megaparsecs and \(d_{pc}\) represents it in parsecs), we can convert our distance uncertainty term to megaparsecs. This is saved under a new column in our data labeled d_ERR_Mpc.

df['d_ERR_pc'] = (np.log(10)/5) * 10**(1+(df.MU/5)) * df.MU_ERR
df['d_ERR_Mpc'] = df.d_ERR_pc * 1E-6

Let’s get back to the construction of our log Likelihood! Instead of using the hubble() function like we did in Part A, we use calc_distance() and the resulting model to calculate our distances (in Mpc). After finding the residuals and each term using our newly calculated d_ERR_Mpc, we return the sum of term1 and term2 as our output.

def ln_likelihood_b(params):
    model = calc_distance(params, df.z)
    residual = df.d_Mpc - model
    term1 = - 0.5 * np.log(2 * np.pi * df.d_ERR_Mpc ** 2)
    term2 = - 0.5 * residual ** 2 / df.d_ERR_Mpc**2
    return sum(term1 + term2)

Finally, we create our log Posterior. This is identical to our log Posterior from Part A, except that it takes multiple parameters instead of one.

def ln_pdf_b(params):
    p = ln_prior_b(params)
    if p == -np.inf:
        return -np.inf
    return p + ln_likelihood_b(params)

Now we can run our MCMC sampler! We choose starting points for each of our parameters, setting h0 to 70 km/s/Mpc (because this is close to our calculated value in Part A), \(\Omega_M\) to 0.3, \(\Omega_k\) to \(1\times10^{-10}\) (a value close to 0), and \(\Omega_\Lambda\) to 0.7, setting the number of walkers to 20, and initializing our sampler using the EnsembleSampler() function from emcee (which takes in our number of walkers, our number of dimensions, and our log Posterior). This time, our starts are calculated using random.multivariate(), which generates a list of multidimensional values centered around our parameter values and with a covariance matrix to control the spread. Then, we run our sampler using the function run_mcmc(), which takes in starts and the number of iterations (as well as an optional progress bar). We ran our sampler for 2000 iterations this time to get an adequate amount of iterations.

params = [70, 0.3, 1E-10, 0.7]
num_walkers_b = 20
sampler_b = emcee.EnsembleSampler(num_walkers_b, 4, ln_pdf_b)
starts_b = np.random.multivariate_normal(
            mean = params,
            cov = [[(params[0]/10)**2,0,0,0],[0,(params[1]/10)**2,0,0],[0,0,(params[2]/10)**2,0],[0,0,0,(params[3]/10)**2]],
            size = num_walkers_b
            )
out = sampler_b.run_mcmc(starts_b, 2000, progress=True)

To create one plot containing all four trace plots for the parameters, we can use subplots() from matplotlib and get_chain() from emcee. Our \(H_0\) trace plot is the only one that appears to have a typical burn-in, where all walkers eventually converge around one value. The three other parameters (\(\Omega_M\), \(\Omega_K\), and \(\Omega_\Lambda\)) appear to start off somewhat concentrated and then proceed to increase in variation. We chose a burn-in point (600) that eliminated this unusual start, which is shown by the red line on each plot.

We can now cut out our burn-in and flatten all walkers into a singular chain for each parameter. We set our burn-in to 600 and use get_chain(), specifying discard=burn_in and flat=True once again.

burn_in_b = 600
